<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Abolitionist and Former Slave to Address Genocide and Slavery in Sudan at UCF</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By UCF Staff
		
		<span class="date">Nov. 12, 2005</span></p>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:sridley@mail.ucf.edu">Sarah Ridley</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-0935</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.ucfglobalperspectives.org/">Global Perspectives Office</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p><span>Francis Bok, a 26-year-old native of Southern Sudan who was enslaved for a decade and wrote about the experience in Escape From Slavery, will speak at 10 a.m. Monday, Nov. 14, at the University of Central Florida.</span></p><p><span></span><span>Bok, who was captured at the age of 7 during a raid on the </span><place /><placetype /><span>village</span></placetype /><span> of </span><placename /><span>Nymlal</span></placename /></place /><span> outside Aweil on </span><date year="1986" day="15" month="5" /><span>May 15, 1986</span></date /><span>, will speak about Genocide and Slavery in </span><country-region /><place /><span>Sudan</span></place /></country-region /><span> in the Pegasus Ballroom of the Student Union. The forum, which is coordinated by the UCF Global Perspectives Office and UCF Office of International Studies as part of International Education Week and the Connecting the University Community program, is free and open to the public.</span></p><p><span></span><span>As Bok was taken into slavery, he saw adults and children brutalized and killed all around him. He was strapped to a donkey and taken north to Kirio. For 10 years, he lived as a family slave and was forced to sleep with cattle, endure daily beatings and eat terrible food.</span></p><p><span></span><span>After his eventual escape, the United Nations resettled him in the </span><country-region /><place /><span>United States</span></place /></country-region /><span>. Bok is now an associate at the American Anti-Slavery Group in </span><city /><place /><span>Boston</span></place /></city /><span>.</span></p><p><span></span><span>Other UCF sponsors include the Office of Undergraduate Studies, </span><place /><placename /><span>Metropolitan</span></placename /><span> </span><placetype /><span>Center</span></placetype /></place /><span> for Regional Studies, Political Science Department, Center for Multilingual Studies, </span><place /><placename /><span>International</span></placename /><span> </span><placename /><span>Services</span></placename /><span> </span><placetype /><span>Center</span></placetype /></place /><span>, </span><place /><placetype /><span>College</span></placetype /><span> of </span><placename /><span>Education</span></placename /></place /><span> and Career Services. Other sponsors are the Orlando Sentinel and the Global Connections Foundation.</span></p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

